description.narrative:
Insatsen ”Georgia Agribusiness Competitiveness” är föreslagen av International Finance Corporation (IFC) i Europa och Asien till Sveriges ambassad i Tbilisi för samfinansiering. Insatsens mål är att stödja Georgiens lagstiftningsreformer för att uppfylla EU-kraven för livsmedelssäkerhet samt att stärka kapaciteten hos lokala aktörer inom jordbruket avseende modern livsmedelssäkerhet och standarder inom sektorn. Insatsen kommer att vara en del av ett större projekt ”Georgia Trade, Investment and Agri-competitiveness”, vilket samfinansieras av IFC och IFC Austria Trust Funds, Swiss State Secretariat for Economic Affairs (SECO) och Multi Donor Trust Funds for Trade Facilitation. Insatsen kommer att utföras genom Världsbanksgruppens (inklusive IFC) gemensamma globala team "Finance, Competitiveness and Innovation practice". Insatsen kommer att genomföras av Världsbanksgruppen under perioden juli 2019 – december 2021. Den totala budgeten för projektet är 16 000 000 SEK, varav Sverige förväntas bidra med 5 700 000 SEK.
Det övergripande målet för projektet “Georgia Trade, Investment and Agri Competitiveness” är att främja hållbar tillväxt driven av privata sektorn i Georgien, genom att stödja den offentliga och privata sektorn med följande:
(i) Komponenten för ökad konkurrenskraft inom jordbruksnäring (Agri Competitiveness Component): Förbättra näringslivets efterlevnad av kraven i EU:s fördjupade frihandelsområde (DCFTA) genom att stödja tillämpningen av nya lagstiftningar inom livsmedelssäkerhet; introducera flexibel tillämpning av standarder för mindre, traditionella livsmedelsproducenter, förbättra biodlingsmetoder för utvalda honungsproducenter; öka kapaciteten hos inspektörer och laboratorier i enlighet med nya krav och med detta, öka honungsexporten till 750 000 USD (basvärdet är 21 200 USD) i december 2022, ett år efter komponentens avslut. (ii) Komponenten för investering (Investment Component): Attrahera och bevara investeringar till ett värde av minst 12 600 000 MUSD, två år efter komponentens avslut. (iii) Komponenten för handel (Trade Component): Effektivisera tullprocedurer genom att etablera ”National Trade Facilitation Committee”, i linje med avtalet för underlättande av handel (Trade Facilitation Agreement) samt effektivisera tullprocedurerna i linje med Världshandelsorganisationens avtal för tullvärdeberäkning.
Georgien är ett land med en liten inhemsk marknad. Landet är importberoende, fattigdomen är utspridd på landsbygden och inkomstfördelningen mellan stad och land är mycket ojämn. Georgien är i stort behov av att effektivisera möjligheterna för exporttillväxt och utveckla produktiviteten i jordbrukssektorn. Under 2017 utgjorde exporten 18 %, en relativt liten del av Georgiens BNP. Frihandelsavtalet med EU har avskaffat importtullar till EU- importerade jordbruksprodukter från Georgien och erbjuder lovande möjligheter för georgiska producenter - förutsatt att landets reglering och kontroll inom livsmedelssäkerheter är i linje med EU-standarder. En flexibel tillämpning av EU-standarder är särskilt viktigt för att säkerställa de små jordbruken, och de små och medelstora livsmedelsproducenternas intressen för framtida marknadssatsningar, både inom EU och internationellt.
Det svenska bidraget avser att stödja reformeringen av reglering för ökad konkurrenskraft inom jordbruksnäringen och med detta påskynda närmandet av Georgiens lagstiftning inom livsmedelssäkerhet till EU standarder; skydda georgiska traditionella producenter genom flexibel tillämpning av standarder; underlätta efterlevnaden av nya standarder och öppna nya marknader (projektpelare 1). Det svenska bidraget avser även att bidra till att utveckla kapaciteten och öka medvetandet för att föra vidare kunskap till den lokala jordbruksnäringen om modern livsmedelssäkerhet och standarder inom sektorn. (projektpelare 2).
Insatsen förväntas bidra till att närma det georgiska regelverket för livsmedelssäkerhet till EU standarder, öka honungsexport till EU och andra utvecklade marknader, och genom att tillämpa flexibelt genomförandet av EU kraven för livsmedelssäkerhet - skydda små lantbrukare och producenter på marknaden.

The intervention "Georgia Agribusiness Competitiveness", proposed by the International Finance Corporation (IFC) in Europe and Central Asia (member of the World Bank Group) to the Embassy of Sweden for co-funding, is aimed at supporting the regulatory reforms of Georgia's food safety legislation with the European Union (EU) requirements and capacity building of local agri-industry on modern food safety and industry standards. The intervention is one of the components of the overall project "Georgia Trade, Investment and Agri Competitiveness", which is co-funded by IFC's and IFC Austria Trust Funds, Swiss State Secretariat for Economic Affairs (SECO) and Multi Donor Trust Funds for Trade Facilitation. The intervention will be executed by the "Finance, Competitiveness and Innovation Practice" , a joint global practice of the World Bank Group (including IFC), during July 2019-December 2021. Total budget of the overall project amounts to 16 000 000 SEK out of which the expected Swedish contribution amounts to 5 700 000 SEK.
The overarching objective of the overall project "Georgia Trade, Investment and Agri Competitiveness" is to promote sustainable private sector-driven growth in Georgia by assisting the public and private sector with the following:
(i) Agri competitiveness component: Improve compliance of businesses with Deep and Comprehensive Free Trade Agreement (DCFTA) requirements by supporting implementation of newly adopted food safety legislation; introducing flexible implementation of standards for small traditional producers; changing beekeeping practice of selected honey producers; increasing capacity of inspectors and laboratory on new requirements and, thus, increasing honey export to USD 750,000 (baseline is USD 21, 200) one year post-completion of the agri competitiveness component in December 2022; (ii) Investment component: Attract and retain investments generating at least 12 600 000 USD of investments two years post-completion of the investment component. (iii) Trade component: Streamline customs procedures through establishment of National Trade Facilitation Committee in line with Trade Facilitation Agreement and streamline customs valuation procedures in line with World Trade Organization (WTO) Customs Valuation Agreement.
Georgia, with its small domestic market, import dependency, widespread rural poverty, and rural-urban income inequality, needs high value-added, efficiency-seeking agri-sector development and export growth. In 2017, export made up a relatively small share of Georgia’s GDP, not more than 18%. The DCFTA, which removes import duties on EU agricultural imports from Georgia, offers promising opportunities for Georgian producers, provided that the country’s food safety regulations and controls are brought in line with EU standards. The flexible implementation of the EU standards is especially important when it comes to safeguarding Georgia’s smallholders and small and medium sized food producers interest in view of future market openings, both in the EU and internationally.
The Swedish contribution envisages to support regulatory reforms in the area of agribusiness competitiveness (project pillar 1) to expedite approximation of Georgia’s food safety legislation with EU requirements, protect Georgia’s traditional producers with the flexible implementation, facilitate compliance with new standards, and open new markets. It is also aimed towards capacity building and awareness creation to transmit knowledge of modern food safety requirements and industry standards to the local agri-industry.
The intervention is expected to contribute to increased EU approximation of the food safety regulations in Georgia, contribute to the increase of honey export to EU and other developed markets and to through flexible implementation of the food safety requirements - protect small producers and farmers on the market.

The overarching objective of the project: Georgia Trade, Investment and Agri Competitiveness is to promote sustainable private sector-driven growth in Georgia. The intervention, targeting the Agri Competitiveness part of the project, is aimed at supporting the regulatory reforms of Georgia's food safety legislation with the European Union (EU) requirements and capacity building of local agri-industry on modern food safety and industry standards. The intervention aims to assist the public and private sector: improve compliance of businesses with the Deep and Comprehensive Free Trade Agreement (DCFTA) requirements by supporting implementation of newly adopted food safety legislation, introduction of flexible implementation of standards for small traditional producers, changing beekeeping practice of selected honey producers, increasing capacity of inspectors and laboratory on new requirements and, thus, growing exports of honey to USD 750,000 (baseline USD 21,200) one year post-completion of agri component (Dec 22); Through carrying out regulatory reforms in the area of agribusiness the intervention aims: (i) to expedite approximation of Georgia’s food safety legislation with EU requirements, protect Georgia’s traditional producers with the flexible implementation, facilitate compliance with new standards, and open new markets. (ii) to transmit knowledge of modern food safety requirements and industry standards to the local agri-industry.

description.narrative: IFC and the Embassy have started partnership on the project: Georgia Agrubusiness Competitevenss since October 2019. The following key results have been acheived from October-December 2019 based on the semi-annual report submitted by the IFC: 1) Training for the Georgian National Food Agency (NFA) staff on flexible implementation of the food hygiene legislation based on EU’s experience. - IFC organized training for the NFA personnel dedicated to demonstrating Latvian experience on the flexible implementation of the EU Food Hygiene Legislation; - Flexible implementation approached which has been effective in the EU, is aimed at protecting the local food production traditions and at the same time helps small and medium-sized primary producers and processors to comply with the regulatory requirements; - Awareness increase on this issue remains important on both public and private levels, as in 2020 regulation on registration of family producers is expected to be enforced in Georgia. 2) Technical assistance to beekeepers IFC started working with nine beekeepers originally, however in the process, two beekeepers did not demonstrate commitment due to lack of interest or lack of resources to upgrade their practices, thus IFC continues working with commited seven beekeepers and searches for new promising beekepers in replacement of the above mentioned two. The challenges in working with the beekeepers as identified by the IFC include the following: 1) majority of the beekeeping sector operate without being legally registered and the beekeepers are not willing to change this practice; 2) beekeepers are reluctant to upgrade their practices and invest in their improvements to become compliant with the regulatory requirements; 3) most of individual beekeepers are not capable to search for the export opportunities by themselves, neither they realize that their product safety or quality might be an obstacle for exports and they need to invest in their improvements. IFC provided the selected beekeepers with on and off-site consultancies in beekeeping and food safety issues, including on the regulatory requirements. Some activities conducted involved: - Beekeepers’ awareness increase on modern beekeeping practices including importance of the apiary monitoring, wax safety control, hive identification and traceability as well as adequate bee disease management. On-site demonstration training in apiary monitoring had been arranged in July 2019 at one of the beekeeper’s farm. All participating beekeepers/honey processors who planned to rearrange their existing facilities or construct new honey processing facilities, were assisted in designing adequate process flow in accordance with the established food safety requirements. and also received individual training in record-keeping practices. IFC has also privided participating beekeepers advisory on Georgian food safety regulatory requirements. - For verification of the the effectiveness of provided consulting assistance and compliance of the beekeepers with the regulatory requirement, IFC in cooperation with The Deutsche Gesellschaft für Internationale Zusammenarbeit (GIZ), NFA and LMA ensured testing of honey samples collected from all participating beekeepers. In total, 25 samples had been tested for antibiotics and pesticides residues at the following laboratories: ALNUMED Lab, Germany (in cooperation with GIZ);BIOR lab, Latvia (in cooperation with the NFA participating beekeepers’ honey samples were included in the national honey monitoring program);LMA, Georgia. Some concrete accomplishments with the beekeepers during the reporting period include the following: - Three beekeepers, who were not registered as the legal entities prior the project, applied for the registration. Summing up to all participating beekeepers being as of now registered as the food business-operators; - For effective traceability and record-keeping beekeepers started identification of hive; - One participant started and completed construction of the new honey processing facility; - One participant started construction of a new honey processing facility; - Five honey samples, which were sent to ALNUMED Lab in Germany, proved to be free from any disallowed residues 3) Building capacity of the Laboratory of the Ministry of Environment Protection and Agriculture (LMA) personnel in honey testing methods - The Project continued providing training to the LMA staff on adopting number of confirmatory test methods aimed at detecting residues of various compounds in the honey including veterinary drugs and pesticides; - Several methods have been completed and validated using in-house method validation, while some are awaiting validation due to busy routine lab schedule, equipment and limited personnel availability for the methods in-house validation.
